cards.title: Meta spent billions to close offices and lay people off. Now we know why.
cards.abstract: Mark Zuckerberg lost $16 billion on the Metaverse last year, but Meta investors are elated because job cuts and office closures led to huge profits.

images.title: Meta spent billions to close offices and lay people off. Now we know why.

highlights.text:
**Meta's Metaverse losses:** Meta lost $16.1 billion on its Reality Labs division, which includes the Metaverse and VR products, in 2023. The losses increased from $13.7 billion in 2022 and are expected to increase further in 2024.

**Meta's stock performance:** Despite the Metaverse losses, Meta's stock is at an all-time high and has risen 12% after its latest earnings release. Meta also announced a stock buyback and a dividend for the first time.

**Meta's cost-cutting measures:** Meta reduced its operating expenses by $3.5 billion in 2023 by closing and combining offices and firing 22% of its employees. This improved its profit margins significantly, as its operating income and profits grew by 62% and 69%, respectively.

cards.title: 2024 Election Map Predicts Joe Biden Will Beat Trump by Even Bigger Margin
cards.abstract: Biden is on track for re-election with two more Electoral College votes than in 2020, according to a new study.

images.title: Donald Trump and Joe Biden
images.caption: Donald Trump speaking to reporters at the International Brotherhood of Teamsters headquarters on January 31, 2024 in Washington, DC (left) and Biden delivering remarks as he attends the Brookland Baptist Banquet Center for their "Sunday Lunch" in West Columbia, South Carolina, on January 28, 2024 (right). A new study suggests Biden is on track to defeat Trump if they faceoff again in November for the presidency.

highlights.text: The article predicts that ***Joe Biden*** will defeat **Donald Trump** in the **2024 presidential election** with **two more electoral college votes** than he won in 2020, assuming they are the respective Democratic and Republican nominees. It cites a study by **Moody's Analytics** that analyzed various factors affecting the election outcome, such as voting trends, approval ratings, and the state of the economy. It shows that Biden could win by a **thin margin** even if he loses **North Carolina** and **Nevada**, but would need to win **Pennsylvania** to reach the required 270 votes. It warns that the election could **flip** with only small shifts in any of these factors, and that it will be **close**. It notes that a recent **Quinnipiac University** poll shows Biden leading Trump by **50 percent to 44 percent** nationally, and by a strong margin among **independent voters**.

subCards.title: Jennifer Crumbley, mom of Michigan school shooter, tries to humanize her embattled family
subCards.abstract: Jennifer Crumbley believed her job as a parent was to protect her son from harm not to protect others from him. Ethan Crumbley killed four at school.

images.title: Jennifer Crumbley looks at the jury as she answers her attorney as she takes the stand in the Oakland County courtroom of Cheryl Matthews on Thursday, Feb. 1, 2024, as she is being tried on four counts of involuntary manslaughter for the four students killed by her son, Ethan Crumbley, in a 2021 shooting at Oxford High School.
images.caption: Jennifer Crumbley looks at the jury as she answers her attorney as she takes the stand in the Oakland County courtroom of Cheryl Matthews on Thursday, Feb. 1, 2024, as she is being tried on four counts of involuntary manslaughter for the four students killed by her son, Ethan Crumbley, in a 2021 shooting at Oxford High School.

highlights.text:
The article reports on ***Jennifer Crumbley's*** testimony in her **historic criminal trial** for involuntary manslaughter in the **Oxford High School mass shooting**. She:

- Denies **ignoring warning signs** or **refusing to bring her son home** after a school counselor and dean of students met with her and her husband over a **violent drawing** he made.
- Shows **photos of their normal family life** and their son's hobbies and grades, and says she never felt he needed **mental health treatment**.
- Explains **text messages** about **demons, ghosts, and Ouija boards** as jokes or harmless activities, and says she was **always worried** about her son's whereabouts.
- Describes **withdrawals from their bank accounts** and **fears of threats** after the shooting, and says she and her husband **fled to a friend's art studio** for safety.
- Admits she felt **bad that her son was sad** and thought she had **failed him**, but says she **never believed he was a danger to others**.

subCards.abstract: It's the first of two storms forecast to wallop California over the next few days with periods of rain, snow, wind and flooding.

highlights.text: The article explains how an ***atmospheric river***, also known as a ***Pineapple Express***, is **pounding California** with heavy rain and snow, triggering **road closures, rockslides, and flooding**. It describes the first storm that hit the **San Francisco Bay Area** on Wednesday and moved south on Thursday, reaching **Los Angeles** in time for the morning commute. It warns of **localized flash flooding** in urban areas, streams, and burn scars, and advises motorists to avoid **Donner Pass**. It forecasts up to **4 feet of snow** for the **Sierra Nevada mountains** and advises winter storm warnings for the region. It warns of a **second storm** that is expected to arrive on Sunday and Monday, which could be **much stronger** and bring **tropical moisture, landslides, and strong winds** to California. It warns that the **cumulative impacts** from the two storms could make the second storm **more extensive and worse** than the first.

He’s exacerbating divisions that extend beyond Eagle Pass, a border town far from home — where DeSantis doesn’t belong and his armed forces aren’t needed. But ...

highlights.text:
The article criticizes ***Florida Gov. Ron DeSantis*** for **sending the State Guard and other state law enforcement resources** to the Texas-Mexico border, where he claims to help **Texas fortify the border and stop the invasion**. It:

- Highlights the **differences and conflicts** between DeSantis and **Texas Gov. Greg Abbott**, who is also deploying state forces to the border, and the **Supreme Court rulings** that limit the authority of state governors to interfere with federal immigration policy and construction of barriers.
- Emphasizes the **risks and dangers** of DeSantis' involvement, such as **provoking the federal government**, **stoking fear and hate** among extremist vigilantes, and **ignoring the real solutions** to the immigration challenges.
- Quotes **Democratic congressional leaders** who warn of **possible violence and consequences** of hate speech and dehumanization at the border, and contrast DeSantis' actions with **President Biden's** efforts to pass **the toughest and fairest set of reforms** to secure the border with his new emergency authority.
- Concludes that the GOP's only hope to win in November is to **keep America fearful** and **attract vigilantes** by sending troops to the border.

cards.title: I Had a Heart Attack at 34. Here’s the First Symptom I Experienced
cards.abstract: The paramedics told my husband I was having a panic attack.

images.title: I Had a Heart Attack at 34. Here’s the First Symptom I Experienced

highlights.text:
In this article, ***Gigi Campos***, a 35-year-old woman, shares her story of **having a heart attack** in February 2023. She explains:

- How she felt **chest pressure** during a morning walk in Miami, Florida, and ignored it as anxiety.
- How she was **misdiagnosed** with premature ventricular contractions (PVCs) and nitroglycerin at the urgent care clinic, and later with cardiac arrest at the ER.
- How she underwent **two stent procedures** to open up blocked arteries and survived cardiac arrest twice.
- How she learned she had **atherosclerosis**, a common condition that causes plaque buildup in the arteries, and was given a 20% chance of another heart attack in her lifetime.
- How she recovered with **cardiac rehab**, joined a **WomenHeart support group**, and took medications to protect her heart.
- How she advises others to **know their risk factors** and **repeat them to doctors**, and to **ask for troponin tests** if they suspect a heart attack.
- How she challenges the **bias** that women in their 30s face when experiencing cardiac issues, and reminds people that **heart attacks are a silent killer**.

cards.title: The 50 most widely seen but universally hated movies of all time
cards.abstract: For fans of "so bad it's good" cinema, Stacker has created a list of 50 of the worst movies that almost everyone watched.

slides.title: Most widely watched but universally hated movies of all time
slides.body:
The 2017 film "The Disaster Artist" tells the story behind the making of "The Room," one of the most famous turkeys of all time. Like Tim Burton's "Ed Wood," James Franco's flick is also a testament to the power of clueless filmmaking and the ridiculous movies that emerge as a result. Despite having widely celebrated actors like Eddie Murphy, established directors like Robert Rodriguez, and esteemed screenwriters like David S. Goyer, these films still managed to disappoint critics and audiences alike.

Notably, many entries are either sequels or adaptations, proving that attempts at creating franchises often fall flat on their faces. These are the true rotten tomatoes and Golden Raspberry Award winners, at least some of which have garnered shocking levels of attention or success despite—or most often because of—their sheer terribleness.

In honor of bad cinema, Stacker has accumulated a list of the most widely watched but universally hated movies of all time. For the data, Stacker searched IMDb for movies with over 50,000 user ratings and ranked the top 50 films, counting down from worse to worst. Ties were broken by votes. Without further delay, here are the most widely watched but universally hated movies of all time.

slides.title: #50. Fifty Shades Darker (2017)
slides.body:
- Director: James Foley
- IMDb user rating: 4.6
- Metascore: 33
- Runtime: 118 minutes

The second installment in the "Fifty Shades" franchise sees the return of Anastasia Steele (Dakota Johnson) and Christian Grey (Jamie Dornan) in this anticipated sequel. The film certainly ups the ante, introducing a stalker, a traumatic origin story for Grey, an abusive boss, and, if that wasn't enough, a helicopter crash. Despite all of this, the film falls flat in creating tension, both dramatic and sexual, and becomes something of a boring mess, earning it "Worst Sequel" at the 38th Golden Raspberry (Razzie) Awards.

A sequel to a spinoff of a far-more-successful film franchise, "Aliens vs. Predator: Requiem," also branded as "AVPR," decided that pitting the titular Aliens and Predators against each other was not enough. Instead, this movie introduces the 'Predalien,' a Predator infected with the Alien, that wreaks havoc on a small town in a bloody but somehow boring massacre. This is the Strause brothers' first film as directors, which becomes apparent in the poorly constructed action sequences and mediocre performances.

highlights.text:
**BYD's first vehicle carrier**

- BYD, the world's largest EV maker, has purchased its first vessel to ship cars around the world.
- The ship, named "BYD Explorer No.1", set sail in January with 5,000 cars on board.
- The ship will help BYD reduce the cost of exporting its cars and meet the growing global demand for its electric vehicles.

**BYD's global market share**

- BYD sold about 3 million cars in 2023, of which 243,000 were exported to countries including Australia, Brazil, and Israel.
- BYD surpassed Tesla for the first time in the fourth quarter of 2023 in terms of exports.
- BYD's more affordable models are well positioned to capture the US market, where customers prioritize price and practicality over style and performance.

cards.abstract: The retailer has faced the same problems as Walmart, Dollar General, and Target but tried to solve them in a different way.

images.title: kroger4
images.caption: A worker pushes grocery carts at a Kroger. Lead JS

highlights.text:
The article examines ***Kroger's*** decision to **end its self-checkout-only experiment** in a Dallas store and revert to traditional checkout lanes. It:

- Provides data on **self-checkout thefts** in grocery stores and their impact on labor costs and store security.
- Describes Kroger's **two self-checkout locations** in the same store and their features, such as wide-belted self-checkouts and staff assistance.
- Explains **customer feedback** and **Kroger's rationale** for switching back to staffed checkout lanes, citing key rivals' similar moves.
- Highlights the **challenges and trade-offs** of self-checkout for retailers, such as item limits, security checks, and customer perception.

cards.title: Donald Trump's Fundraising Plummets
cards.abstract: Trump's campaign team raised $19 million during the last three months of 2023, down from $24.5 million in the third quarter.

images.title: Donald Trump in Nevada
images.caption: Republican presidential candidate and former U.S. President Donald Trump speaks during a campaign event at Big League Dreams Las Vegas on January 27, 2024 in Las Vegas, Nevada. Trump's election campaign reported raising $19 million during the final quarter of 2023.

highlights.text:
The article reports on ***Donald Trump's*** fundraising performance in the **fourth quarter of 2023** for his presidential and 2024 campaign. It shows that:

- The campaign raised **$19 million** in the quarter, a **20 percent drop** from the previous quarter, and ended the year with **$33 million** in cash.
- This amount is **lower than** that of **President Joe Biden's** campaign, which raised **$33 million** in the same quarter and has **$46 million** in cash.
- Trump **outraised** his only remaining GOP rival, **Nikki Haley**, who raised **$17 million** in the quarter.
- The campaign spent **tens of millions** of dollars on **legal fees** via two PACs, bringing the total amount of donor money on legal expenses last year to **around $50 million**.
- Trump has pleaded **not guilty** to **91 felony charges** and denied all wrongdoing in several civil cases, which could impose **hundreds of millions of dollars** in fines on him.

cards.title: The 10 movies everyone's watching on Netflix right now
cards.abstract: Stacker compiled a list of the most watched movies on Netflix using data from the company's website.

slides.title: Most popular movies on Netflix last week
slides.body:
You may expect folks to be streaming the recently announced Oscar-nominated movies with the awards right around the corner. Even though quite a few are available on Netflix—like "Maestro," "Nimona," "Nyad," "Rustin," and "Spider-Man: Across the Spider-Verse"—the streaming service's most recent movies chart indicates that audiences are choosing nail-biting thrills over awards darlings.

"Dumb Money," a captivating comedy-drama that delves into the world of financial risk, quickly climbed up the most-watched movies chart after its Jan. 21 release on Netflix. The true story centers on a group of inexperienced investors led by real-life analyst Keith Gill (played by Paul Dano), who invests in an ailing GameStop stock because he continues to believe in its potential. Motivated by the promise of "sticking it to the man," they embark on a GameStop short squeeze, throwing the stock market on its head. As the 2023 film unfolds, the characters face unforeseen challenges, testing their impulsive financial choices and decision-making abilities.

Another feature that's riveting Netflix subscribers is "The Postcard Killings" despite receiving poor box office numbers when it was released in theaters in 2020. The crime thriller—which joined Netflix on Jan. 15—follows NYPD detective Jacob Kanon (played by Jeffrey Dean Morgan) as he investigates the death of his daughter, which leads him to unravel a series of gruesome interconnected murders across Europe. Directed by Danis Tanović, "The Postcard Killings" is based on James Patterson and Liza Marklund's novel of the same name.

Also action-packed is "Blood and Bone," a gripping 2009 martial arts film that joined Netflix on Jan. 18. It's the story of Isaiah Bone (played by Michael Jai White) who navigates the dangerous underground world of illegal fighting, seeking redemption for a mysterious past. He becomes entangled in a web of deceit and betrayal as he rises through the ranks of the brutal fight circuit.   

Find out how all these films rank on the list Stacker compiled of the most popular movies on Netflix in the U.S. from Jan. 22-Jan. 28.

cards.title: Want a Healthier Heart? Eat These 5 Types of Foods
cards.abstract: Adding more nutrition to your diet can help keep your blood pressure in check, lower your cholesterol and improve your cardiovascular health.

images.title: 5 Foods to Boost Your Heart Health

topQuestions.q: Why is it important to learn your blood type and how does it affect your risk of cardiovascular conditions?

highlights.text:
The article explains what a ***heart-healthy diet*** is and what foods to eat for it. It covers:

- **Fruits and vegetables** for their high nutritional density and benefits for blood pressure, cholesterol and artery health.
- **Whole grains** for their fiber, vitamins and minerals that lower cholesterol and blood pressure.
- **Lean and plant protein** from sources like beans, nuts, seeds, tofu, fish, eggs and poultry for their protein content and omega-3 fatty acids.
- **Healthy fats** from sources like olive oil, sesame oil, avocados and plant oils for their role in heart function and health.
- **Heart-check foods** that have the Heart-Check seal from the American Heart Association for their specific cardiovascular benefits.

The article advises to eat these foods in moderation, choose plant-based protein over red and processed meat, and pair the diet with other heart health boosters like exercise, sleep and stress management. It also suggests learning one's blood type to understand one's risk of certain cardiovascular conditions.

cards.title: Groundhog Day: Some States Getting Six More Weeks of Winter
cards.abstract: Punxsutawney Phil will make his prediction but data points to a mixed bag for the United States.

images.title: A handler holds Punxsutawney Phil, the weather prognosticating groundhog, during the 137th celebration of Groundhog Day in Punxsutawney, Pa., in 2023.
images.caption: Barry Reeger

highlights.text: The article explains the origin and significance of ***Groundhog Day*** and the prediction of **six more weeks of winter** or an early spring by *Punxsutawney Phil*, the groundhog. It provides historical and meteorological data on the groundhog's accuracy, showing that it has **predicted 108 winters and only 20 springs** in more than 120 years. It also outlines the weather patterns and forecasts for different states and regions in the U.S., indicating that **El Nino** is likely to cause **warmer temperatures** for half of the states this year, especially in the **Northern states**. It notes that **winter is expected to continue** for the **West Coast states**, and that some states, such as **Minnesota, North Dakota, and Montana**, will feel like spring has sprung early throughout the month. It concludes that the groundhog's track record suggests a **longer winter** is more likely than an **early spring**, but that this year might be different depending on the groundhog's verdict.

cards.abstract: KYIV, Ukraine (AP) — Ukraine claimed Thursday it used sea drones to sink a small Russian warship in the Black Sea as Russian investigators alleged that a Russian military transport plane that crashed last month was brought down by two U.S.-made Patriot missiles fired by Kyiv’s forces. Ukraine’s military intelligence agency, known by its Ukrainian acronym GUR, published a video that it said showed naval drones assaulting the Russian missile-armed...

highlights.text:
The article reports on the ***Ukrainian claim*** of using **sea drones** to **sink a Russian warship** in the *Black Sea* and the **Russian response** of blaming **U.S.-made Patriot missiles** for **downing a Russian military transport plane**. 

- Ukraine's military intelligence agency, **GUR**, published a video showing *naval drones* crashing into and exploding on the **Russian corvette Ivanovets**, which was on patrol on *Lake Donuzlav* in western Crimea. GUR said the ship cost **$60 million-$70 million** and was sunk.
- A Western official backed the Ukrainian account, saying it was **"highly likely"** that *uncrewed surface vessels* were responsible for the strike.
- Russian officials made no immediate comment on the Ivanovets.
- Ukrainian attacks on Russian aircraft and ships in the Black Sea have helped push Moscow's naval forces back, allowing Kyiv to increase crucial exports of grain and other goods through its southern ports.
- Ukrainian army chief, **Gen. Valerii Zaluzhnyi**, wrote an opinion piece for CNN, outlining his assessment of the state of the war and laying out priorities for Ukraine in 2024, such as creating a system for high-tech assets, introducing a new philosophy of training and warfare, and mastering new combat capabilities.
- Russia's Investigative Committee said it deduced that the **Russian Il-76 military transport plane** that crashed near the border with Ukraine on **Jan. 24** was downed using the **U.S.-made Patriot air defense system**, which Western allies have supplied to Kyiv. It produced no physical evidence for its claims.
